---
description: Use the tools the codebase is configured for
globs:
alwaysApply: true
---

- Use pnpm not npm!
- The source of truth for Node.js version is the root `package.json` `engines.node` field. Your shell should be configured to respect that (e.g. Volta, or nvm/fnm with a matching `.nvmrc`). If it is not—e.g. you see a wrong `node -v` or Node/pnpm commands fail due to version—report to the user: "Your shell is misconfigured for this repo. Use the Node version in the root package.json engines field. Configure a version manager (Volta, nvm, fnm) to respect it, or run `nvm use` / `fnm use` / equivalent in this directory before running commands." Otherwise, before running Node.js or pnpm commands you may run `nvm use` or the user's local equivalent to ensure the correct version is active.
- We use turborepo to build, generally. `pnpm build` scripts are available in each package which delegate to turborepo
- When you want to typecheck, use the local `pnpm typecheck` scripts instead of writing `tsc` commands from scratch
- When you want to test, use the local `pnpm test` scripts. For coverage, use `pnpm test:coverage` (all packages) or `pnpm coverage:packages` (packages only, excludes examples)
- Use arktype instead of zod
- Never add file extensions to imports in TypeScript
- Don't add comments if avoidable, prefer code which expresses its intent
- Don't add exports for backwards compatibility unless requested to do so
- Always write tests before creating or modifying implementation
- Do not reexport things from one file in another, except in the `exports/` folders
